In the Second Battle of Z<U+00FC>rich, the French regained control of the city, along with the rest of Switzerland. Notably, Massena outgeneraled Korsakov; surrounded him, tricked him, and then took more than half his army as a prisoner, plus captured the baggage train and most of his cannons, and inflicting over 8,000 casualties.<ref>Thiers, p. 400&nbsp;401.</ref>   Most of the fighting took place on both banks of the river [[Limmat]] up to the gates of Z<U+00FC>rich, and in part within the city itself. Z<U+00FC>rich had declared itself neutral, and was spared general destruction.  General [[Nicolas Charles Oudinot|Oudinot]] commanded the French forces on the right bank and general [[<U+00C9>douard Adolphe Casimir Joseph Mortier|Joseph Mortier]] those on the left.<ref>Blanning, p. 253; {{de icon}} H<U+00FC>rlimann, [http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D19630.phpHotz "(Johann Konrad) Friedrich von Hotze,"]; Longworth, p. 270.</ref> 

At the same time, [[Nicolas Jean de Dieu Soult|Soult]]  led a small force, some 150 musket-men, across the river [[Linth]]<U+2014>the men held their muskets over their heads and waded across, through water to their chests<U+2014>and protected the crossing site for the remainder of the force.  Baron von Hotze, commander of the Austrian force there, advanced on the position near [[Richterswil]] to direct its defense, and was killed by a French musket ball. His successor, [[Franz, Baron von Petrasch]], could not throw the French back, and organized a retreat from the region, falling back to St. Gallen and losing 8,000&nbsp;men and some guns.<ref>Lina Hug and Richard Stead. ''Switzerland''.  New York, G.P. Putnam's Sons, 1902, p. 361; Thiers, p. 401<U+2013>402.</ref> By the time Suvorov arrived in St. Gallen in early October, the Austrians and the Russians had been pushed out and he was forced to lead his men over the Alps to the Voralberg, resulting in additional losses.<ref>Longworth, pp. 270<U+2013>271.</ref>

== Subsequent variations ==
The [[Arm<U+00E9>e d'Helv<U+00E9>tie|Army of Switzerland]] and portions of the Army of the Danube merged in a joint command under Andre Massena in April 1799; in June, portions of the Army of the Danube were used to form the  [[Arm<U+00E9>e du Rhin|Army of the Rhine]].  Both the Army of the Rhine and the Army of the Danube subsequently merged in 24&nbsp;November 1799&nbsp;to form a new, enlarged army designated the Army of the Rhine.<ref>Adolphe Thiers. ''The history of the French revolution'', New York: Appleton, 1854, v. 4., p. 370.</ref>

